          "text": "Let me review this thoroughly - both correctness of the task logic and C++ idiomatic style.\n\n**By task requirements:**\n1. Read points x y z from stdin until EOF ✓\n2. Output point count ✓ (line 74)\n3. Min/max per axis (bounding box) ✓ (lines 85-98, output at line 100)\n4. Centroid ✓ (lines 95-97 sum, 104-106 divide)\n5. Average distance to centroid ✓ (lines 111-117)\n6. 3 decimal places ✓ (using {:.3f})\n7. Error handling with exit codes ✓ (io_fail, data, no_in)\n8. Line numbers in error messages ✓\n9. Empty input → no_in ✓\n\n**Correctness issues:**\n\n1. **`std::hypot` with 3 arguments (C++17)** — `std::hypot(x, y, z)` computes `sqrt(x² + y² + z²)`. This is correct for Euclidean distance.\n\n2. **Centroid computation uses center.x, center.y, center.z** — It starts as `Point center{};` (zero-initialized), accumulates sum in the loop, then divides. Correct.\n\n3. **Average distance is computed AFTER centroid is finalized** — Correct, the second loop uses the finalized centroid.\n\n4. **`long double dist`** — why `long double`? The points are `double`. `std::hypot` returns `double`. Storing in `long double` is unnecessary precision promotion. Should be `double dist`. Not a bug, just odd.\n\n5. **`int i` for line counter** — `i` counts lines, but what if there are more than 2^31-1 lines? Not a concern for this task (N ≤ 20 from task 1 logic, or \"массовый вход\" 10⁶). But... `i` is used only for error messages, so it's fine.\n\n**Idiomatic C++ issues:**\n\n1. **`main(void)` — C-ism** → `main()` (void is redundant in C++). But this is minor and harmless.\n\n2. **Variable naming `minimum`/`maximum`** — I already mentioned this. The names are misleading.\n\n3. **`std::cout` for \"Количество точек\"** — Should be `std::print` like the rest of the formatted output. Mixing `<<` and `std::print` is inconsistent.\n\n4. **`std::hypot` with three args** — C++17 feature. `std::hypot(x, y, z)` is correct but maybe less known. Could also use `std::sqrt(...)`