ic_limits<double>::lowest()};\n    Point min_border {std::numeric_limits<double>::max(),\n                      std::numeric_limits<double>::max(),\n                      std::numeric_limits<double>::max()};\n    ```\n    Or use `std::numeric_limits<double>::infinity()`.\n\n    But removing the temporary variables would also eliminate the confusing naming. Not a bug, but a code smell.\n\n14. **`points.size()` called 3 times** (lines 74, 104-106, 115) — Could store `std::size_t n = points.size();` once. But this is minor.\n\n15. **`dist = dist / points.size()`** — Integer division promotion: `points.size()` is `std::size_t` (unsigned). `dist / points.size()` promotes to `long double` because `dist` is `long double`. So no truncation. But if `dist` were `double`, the expression would still promote to `double` (the common arithmetic conversion promotes to the larger type). Actually... `double / size_t` → `double / double` after conversion. So it's fine either way. But using `static_cast<double>(points.size())` is more explicit.\n\nWait, I said `long double dist` is odd. Let me think again. `std::hypot` returns `double` (since all arguments are `double`), so accumulation into `long double` gives more precision, which is technically fine but unnecessary. The final result is printed with `{:.3f}`, so any extra precision is lost anyway. Using `double` would be more consistent.\n\nLet me also check: `std::hypot` with 3 arguments. Is this available in C++17? Yes, `std::hypot` has a 3-argument overload since C++11:\n```cpp\nfloat hypot(float x, float y, float z);\ndouble hypot(double x, double y, double z);\nlong double hypot(long double x, long double y, long double z);\n```\n(from cppreference). So it's fine.\n\nNow, let me also think about whether the format strings in `std::print` are correct. The format specifier `{:.3f}` should work for `double`. Yes.\n\nLet me also note: the `setlocale` is `\"Russian.Russia_1251\"` — this is still wrong! It should be `\"Russian_Russia.