          "text": "The user is asking why I used both `if errorlevel 66` and `if not errorlevel 65` instead of just `if not errorlevel 65`. Let me explain how errorlevel checking works in batch files.\n\nIn batch, `if errorlevel N` means \"if errorlevel is N or greater\". So:\n- `if errorlevel 65` → true for exit codes 65, 66, 67, etc.\n- `if not errorlevel 65` → true for exit codes 0-64 (i.e. less than 65)\n- `if not errorlevel 66` → true for exit codes 0-65\n\nSo `if not errorlevel 65` alone would be true for exit code 0 too, which wouldn't distinguish \"success\" from \"data error\".\n\nThe correct way to check for a specific exit code in batch is:\n1. `if errorlevel 66` — true if exit >= 66\n2. `if not errorlevel 65` — true if exit < 65 (i.e. <= 64)\n\nCombined: `if errorlevel 66` catches exit codes >= 66 (like 66, 67, etc.), and then `if not errorlevel 65` catches exit codes <= 64 (like 0, 64). If neither is true, we know exit is exactly 65.\n\nSo the pattern `if errorlevel 66 ... else if not errorlevel 65 ... else exit is 65` is the batch idiom.\n\nBut actually, a simpler way: since we know the expected code is 65, we could just check errorlevel >= 65 AND not errorlevel >= 66. But actually, the simplest single-line check in batch would be:\n- Check `if errorlevel 65 if not errorlevel 66` — but this only works in cmd.exe? Actually, `if errorlevel 65 if not errorlevel 66` is valid.\n\nOr even simpler: check the exact value by subtraction or comparison tricks, but they're fragile.\n\nThe two-line approach I showed is the idiomatic batch way.",
